### Orchestrator refactoring

Adopting SandboxAgent means splitting the orchestrator into two dispatch paths:

| Agent type | Dispatch | Loop owner | Tool governance |
|-----------|----------|------------|-----------------|
| **Brain-native** (chat, PM, observer, analytics) | AI SDK `generateText` | Brain orchestrator | Proxy executes all tools |
| **Coding** (Claude Code, Codex, Amp, etc.) | SandboxAgent SDK | Agent process in sandbox | Dynamic MCP endpoint `/mcp/agent/<name>` |

The orchestrator currently manages all agents through AI SDK tool loops. With SandboxAgent, coding agent sessions would use:

```typescript
// Spawn coding agent in sandbox
const session = await sdk.createSession({
  agent: "claude",
  cwd: "/workspace",
});

// Configure Brain as the LLM proxy and MCP tool provider
await sdk.setMcpConfig("/workspace", "brain", {
  type: "remote",
  url: `${brainUrl}/mcp/agent/${agentName}`,
  transport: "sse",
  headers: { "X-Brain-Auth": agentToken },
});

// Prompt and stream events
const stream = await sdk.prompt(session.id, { message: taskDescription });
for await (const event of stream) {
  // Ingest into Brain trace graph
}
```

Brain-native agents remain unchanged — they run in-process with AI SDK and the proxy's full tool loop. The orchestrator dispatches based on agent type.

### Priority consideration

SandboxAgent becomes valuable when Brain needs to run **coding agents** (Claude Code, Codex) in sandboxes for software engineering tasks. If the current focus is on chat agents and knowledge graph management (which run in Brain's own process), SandboxAgent can be deferred until the coding agent use case is prioritized.

